search_all: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI Regularly Scheduled Series RSS Live Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient. title: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI
search_all: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI Regularly Scheduled Series RSS Live Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). [1].  This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient.  The program will also explore the relationhsip among emergency physicians and cardiologists, and how that relationship can best be managed to improve patient care.  02/17/2005  2005  02

title: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI
search_all: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI Regularly Scheduled Series RSS Live Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). [1].  This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient.  The program will also explore the relationhsip among emergency physicians and cardiologists, and how that relationship can best be managed to improve patient care.  03/17/2005  2005  03

title: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI
search_all: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI Regularly Scheduled Series RSS Live Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). [1].  This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient.  The program will also explore the relationhsip among emergency physicians and cardiologists, and how that relationship can best be managed to improve patient care.  04/07/2005  2005  04
description: Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). [1].  This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient.  The program will also explore the relationhsip among emergency physicians and cardiologists, and how that relationship can best be managed to improve patient care.

title: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI
search_all: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI Regularly Scheduled Series RSS Live Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). [1].  This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient.  The program will also explore the relationhsip among emergency physicians and cardiologists, and how that relationship can best be managed to improve patient care.  04/21/2005  2005  04
description: Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). [1].  This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient.  The program will also explore the relationhsip among emergency physicians and cardiologists, and how that relationship can best be managed to improve patient care.

title: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI
search_all: From Presentation to Intervention Redefining Early Aggressive Therapy of UA/NSTEMI Regularly Scheduled Series RSS Live Until 1996, unfractionated heparin (UFH), in conjunction with aspirin, constituted the principal means of affecting the thrombotic process in unstable angina (UA)/non-ST-elevation myocardial  infarction (NSTEMI). [1].  This program will consider data from studies of antiplatelet and antithrombin agents, data that in many cases post-dates the ACC/AHA guidelines, and, given that data, seek to define what constitutes appropriate antithrombotic therapy of the high-risk UA/NSTEMMI patient.  The program will also explore the relationhsip among emergency physicians and cardiologists, and how that relationship can best be managed to improve patient care.  05/19/2005  2005  05

title: The Eighth Cincinnati Neurofest: Neurodevelopment and Brain Function
search_all: The Eighth Cincinnati Neurofest: Neurodevelopment and Brain Function Course  Live Scientific progress of the past decade demonstrates that studies of neural development are crucial for the understanding of brain function and disorders.  Pathways identified in model organisms, such as Drosophila and mouse, are revelant to human neurodevelopment.  Likewise, certain genes found mutated in human diseases have been shown to serve critical roles in neural development.  Moreover, the identification and isolation of neural stem cell inspires new opportunities for tissue and cell therapies.  The purpose of this symposium is to highlight current advances in our understanding of the signals and factors that control and guide nervous system development.  Moreover, this knowledge may provide new perspectives on treating human neurological and psychiatric disorders.   Topics will include stem cells, axon guidance, cell migration, Drosophila models, neuron and glia-fate determination and neuronal plasticity.  04/12/2002  2002  04

title: Horizons in Clinical Practice: The New Genetics and Evidence-Based Medicine
search_all:
Horizons in Clinical Practice: The New Genetics and Evidence-Based Medicine Course  Live Medical science is expanding rapidly in virtually all areas.  This program combines an overview of genetics research and clinical applications with the new emerging emphasis on evidence-based medicine.  Genetics  research promises to completely revolutionize the way medicine is practiced.  From the completion of the human genome project to designer drugs, clinicians will learn about the impact on patient care in the near future.

As medical knowledge expands at an exponential rate clinicans are faced with the need to manage overwhelming amounts of new information and research.  In this climate of instant access to a vast array of new treatments and diagnostic procedures clinicians are being challenged to show the evidence for their clinical decisions and practice patterns.  New resources are emerging to help physicians condense conflicting research findings and opinions.  This program describes these resources and how they are being used in practice and education.  11/16/2002  2002  11

title: Modern Advances in the Diagnosis and Treatment of Cardio & Neurovascular Emergencies
search_all: Modern Advances in the Diagnosis and Treatment of Cardio & Neurovascular Emergencies Course  Live Patients presenting with chest pain to the Emergency Department remain a major clinical challenge.  In the United States there are over 5 million annual visits for this problem, resulting in 2 million hospital admissions.  Nontraumatic chest discomfort remains the primary catalyst for patient evaluation of possible ACS (including unstable angina, non-Q Wave, MI and ST-segment elevation) in the ED.  In addition, up to 1 million patients present to the ED with stroke each year.  Therefore, it is critical for the emergency physician community to remain on the forefront of state-of-the-art diagnostic and treatment options involving the newest therapeutic regimens, such as GP IIb-IIIa inhibitor therapy, low moelcular weight heparin, and combination therapy to care for patients with ACS and stroke.  In addition, the diagnosis and treatment of congestive heart failure and stroke are critically important to emergency physicians and healthcare providers.  05/19/2002  2002  05

In addition up to 1 million patients present to the ED with stroke each year.  Therefore, it is critical for the emergency physician community to remain on the forefront of state-of-the-art diagnostic and treatment options involving the newest therapeutic regimens, such as GP IIb-IIIa inhibitor therapy, low molecular weight heparin, and combination therapy to care for patients with ACS and strok.  W. Brian Gibler and the Emergency Medicine Cardiac Research and Educational Group International (EMCREG) are pleased to present an exciting educational forum in emergency cardiovascular and neurovascular care for emergency physicians, emergency nurses, and other healthcare providers involved in the management of patients with ACS and stroke.  10/07/2002  2002  10

title: Approaches to Intervention in ACS: Are We Sufficiently Aggressive?
search_all: Approaches to Intervention in ACS: Are We Sufficiently Aggressive? Course  Live There continues to be  great advances in the pharmacotherapy of the acute coronary syndromes (ACS).  In March 2002, the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association released updated guidelines for UA/NSTEMI in which the roles of newer antiplatelet and anticoagulant agents in patient management were better defined.  Several recently reported clinical trials are refining our understanding of how to optimize anticoagulant and antiplatelet therapy in patients undergoing thrombolysis for STEMI.  In addition, the results of trials such as DANAMI-2 and C-PORT have shed further light on the value of primary percutaneous intervention (PCI) in this clinical setting.  It is critical for cardiologists to be cognizant not only of these trials' results and implications, but they must define the circumstances when thrombolysis and or primary PCI is preferred.  09/26/2002  2002  09

title: Transitions: Exploring Women's Mental Health Through the Life Span: Workshop 4 Middle Ages 31-60 Yrs
search_all: Transitions: Exploring Women's Mental Health Through the Life Span: Workshop 4 Middle Ages 31-60 Yrs Course  Live Mental Illnesses affect women and men differently some disorders are more common in women, some express themselves with different symptoms.  In most studies, females have twice the rate of men for depression and anxiety disorders, and higher rates for eating and somatoform disorders.  Whether one is male or female consistently emerges as one of the statistically strongest demongraphic correlates of risk for different types of mental illness.  Transitions: Exploring Women's Mental Health Through Life Span will bring to light current research findings on mental health issues from birth to older adulthood.  Participants will garner gender-specific information for the diagnosis and treatment of mental disorders in children and women as well as issues addressing mental well being.  11/18/2002  2002  11

search_all: International Society for Clinical Densitometry Certification Program Course  Live There are approximately 12,000 DXA instruments in the U.S. for measuring bone density. title: State-Of-The-Art Update On The Management Of HIV Infection
search_all: State-Of-The-Art Update On The Management Of HIV Infection Course  Live The purpose of this symposium is to provide a state-of-the-art update on the management of HIV infection.  The target audience are physicians and allied health personnel that provide care to persons with HIV infection.  Recent findings will be discussed from the 10th Conference on Retroviruses, the 4th Annual Meeting on Lipodystrophy, and the Viral Resistance Meetings.  This half-day symposium will cover the following topics: The management of HIV infection in women and how this differs with men; update on the pathogenesis of HIV infection; and update on recent research findings for HIV that impact management.  There will be case presentation session that will be interactive with the audience to illustrate specific management points.  Participants will have an opportunity to ask questions and there will be a panel discussion.  03/08/2003  2003  03

title: Spasticity Management: Concepts, Applications & Prospects
search_all: Spasticity Management: Concepts, Applications & Prospects Course  Live Several new spasticity management techniques have been validated in recent years (e.g., Botulinum Toxin A, Botulinum Toxin B).  Considerable interest exists, but information on how to administer these techniques is not readily available or widely published for the practitioner.  Other techniques (e.g. bracing, splinting) have questionable efficacy, or their efficacy has not been examined.  This conference would examine and review these issues in detail.  04/04/2003  2003  04

search_all: 4th Annual Bone Day: Modern Approaches to Diagnosis & Treatment of Osteoporosis Course  Live Osteoporosis continues to be a major public health problem, with an enormous cost. title: Health for Success: Addressing Obesity Through a Coordinated School Health Approach
search_all: Health for Success: Addressing Obesity Through a Coordinated School Health Approach Course  Live The medical reason for this program is to inform the community about the significant trends in obesity in children and how to combat the alarming increases.  Obesity is on the rise nationally and has many health consequences for children.  The number of NIDDM cases at Children's Hospital is on the rise as well as increasing diagnoses of hypertension, high cholesterol and joint problems.  Prevention is an essential component of improving the prognosis for our area and can only be accomplished with participation of the whole community.  The physician has a key role in leading the team, and must be a part of changing environment.  The key changes involve nutritional habits and physicial activity.  05/01/2003  2003  05

title: Urologic Management of Overactive Bladder with and without Chronic Pelvic Pain
search_all: Urologic Management of Overactive Bladder with and without Chronic Pelvic Pain Course  Live There are approximatelyh 33 million individuals in the United States suffering from overactive bladder, and over half of these individuals are women.  Recent epidemiology studies indicate that 55% of these women also have urinary incontinence, (OAB wet).  A significant number of these OAB wet patients seek, but do not receive, help for their condition.  Individuals suffering from chronic pelvic pain are also of concern, since the number of cases is estimated at 14 million.  Many of these patients' pain is of bladder origin and present as OAB dry patients.  Recent articles and scientific studies reinforce the idea that there is a need to review current clinical evaluation, understand the differential diagnosis, and effectively  manage these conditions.  09/13/2003  2003  09

This educational seminar is part of a comprehensive program to implement best practice treatment guidelines through the Ohio Department of Mental Health.

title: Migraine Headache in Primary Care
search_all: Migraine Headache in Primary Care Course  Live Migraine headache is one of the most common disorders encountered by primary care physicians.  It is more common than asthma, hypertension and osteoarthritis!  Yet so little time has been spent educating primary care physicians on this disabling disorder.  We offer you the opportunity to participate in this "unique educational experience" at the University of Cincinnati. This course will be very interactive and all participants will perform a "simulated office visit" with a standardized patient to perfect interviewing and management skills.  The first course will address the diagnosis and treatment of migrain headache, while the second course offered in November, 2003 will address issues related to the difficult headache patient.  You are encouraged to attend both courses!  Attedance of this course will enable you to develop special expertise in the management of headache patients within your primary care practices.  06/25/2003  2003  06

title: State of the Art Management of HIV Infection
search_all: State of the Art Management of HIV Infection Course  Live The purpose of this symposium is to provide a state-of-the-art update on the management of HIV infection.  Recent findings will be discussed from Interscience Conference on Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy, Infectious Disease Society of America, and International AIDS Society Meeting.  This half day symposium will cover the following topics: An update on HIV drug resistance and management strategies, diagnosis and management of anal cancer/HPV infection, strategies to manage HIV infection and complications. Participants will have an opportunity to ask questions and there will be a panel discussion.  10/25/2003  2003  10

title: 6th Annual Cardiovascular & Neurovascular Emergencies: Implications For Clinical Practice
search_all: 6th Annual Cardiovascular & Neurovascular Emergencies: Implications For Clinical Practice Course  Live Patients presenting with chest pain to the Emergency Department remain a major clinical challenge.  In the United States alone there are over 8 million annual visits for this problem, resulting in two million hospital admissions.  Nontraumatic chest discomfort remains the primary catalyst for patient evaluation of possible ACS (including unstable angina, non-Q Wave MI and ST-segment elevation) in the ED.  In addition, up to 1 million patients present to the ED with stroke each year.  10/11/2003  2003  10

title: Management of the Challenging Headache Patient: What You Need to Know
search_all: Management of the Challenging Headache Patient: What You Need to Know Course  Live Chronic daily headache occurs in 1-3% of the United States population and represents a challenge to primary care physicians and specialists alike.  This unique course combines interactive didactive lectures with "real life interviews" of standardized patients to enable participants to manage these complex patients.  Topics to be addressed in this symposium include diagnosis and management of menstrual migraine, co-morbid diseases (psychiatric and other neurologic diseases) and medications overuse headaches.  You will also learn appropriate use of narcotic medications and identification of headache trigger factors.  At the completion of the program you will receive a certificate that you have completed the University of Cincinnati mini-fellowship in headache.  11/01/2003  2003  11

title: Examination of the Lower Quarter: Biomechanics
search_all: Examination of the Lower Quarter: Biomechanics Course  Live This evidence-based course incorporates focused laboratory sessions to review the mechanics of the lower kinetic chain, particularly those related to ankle, knee, and hip pathologies.  You'll review current research findings in gain analysis, lower limb function, and joint biomechanics and discuss implications for evaluation and treatment of various musculoskeletal conditions.  Participants will be provided with practical information to take back to the clinic, including the opportunity to develop observational gait analysis skills.  11/08/2003  2003  11

title: Cincinnati Hemodialysis Vascular Access Symposium - 2004
search_all: Cincinnati Hemodialysis Vascular Access Symposium - 2004 Course  Live The Cincinnati Hemodialysis Vascular Access Symposium is a multidisciplinary conference which is devoted entirely to the emerging specialty of dialysis access.  An internationally recognized faculty will take participants through all the multiple issues that play a role in this complex and evolving area.  Special emphasis will be placed on the devlopement of a team approach and on the introduction of novel protocols (both therapeutic and logistic) into this field.   We hope that this will be a forum to share and discuss new ideas and to try and find solutions for old problems so that we can take better care of our patients.  We look forward to seeing you in Cincinnati.  03/19/2004  2004  03

title: CMRS 2004 Annual Society Meeting
search_all: CMRS 2004 Annual Society Meeting Course  Live A fundamental focus of the clinical Magnetic Resonance Society is continuing education for the diagnostic imaging professional actively engaged in the clinical practice of MRI.  The annual meeting is an outstanding teaching forum with emphasis on practical, clinical information that can immediately be put into practice.  An outstanding faculty specifically chosen for their teaching ability and dedication to the CMRS mission will discuss expanded applications, appropriate protocols and new developments.  This meeting is for physicians, scientists, and technologists.  Thursday offers a comprehensive course in musculoskeletal MRI.  Friday and Saturday focus on brain and spine and Sunday focuses on cardiac MRI and MRA.  06/24/2004  2004  06

title: Achieving the Transformation of Mental Health Care in Ohio: An Update & Dialogue
search_all: Achieving the Transformation of Mental Health Care in Ohio: An Update & Dialogue Course  Live The President's New Freedom Commission on Mental Health has made recommendations for all states.  We are now responsible to promote the New Freedom Commissions recommendations for the state of Ohio to transform mental health care.  Since some information of mental health care in Ohio is anecdotal, a formal survey was drafted to gain a clearer picture of what is acutally happening.  The data presented will tell us what we can do to plan the future.  There will be discussions on primary care providers providing mental health care and how they could collaborate to provide better care.  Finally , with suicide being problematic, we have recruited an expert on suicide prevention with the assistance of community coalitions.  There will be discussion on what they are, their effectiveness and how they can be developed.  05/26/2004  2004  05

title: Helping Children & Adolescents with Bipolar Disorder Succeed: Current Research & Strategies
search_all: Helping Children & Adolescents with Bipolar Disorder Succeed: Current Research & Strategies Course  Live Bipolar Disorder (BPD) are severe and persistent, or cyclic disorders occuring in approximately 1% of adults (Myers, Weissman etal.1984).  These disorders are also the most prevalent of psychotic disorders across all age groups including children and adolescents.  These disorders now recognized as equally as prevalent in children and adolescents-estimated prevalence of 1%.  The purpose of this program is two fold: to discuss and illustrate the various presentations of bipolar disorders in childlren, adolescents and young adults; and to discuss various treatment options currently available.  09/18/2004  2004  09

title: ISCD Annual Meeting 2005: New Directions
search_all: ISCD Annual Meeting 2005: New Directions Course  Live This program for the International Society of Clinical Densitometry annual meeting will address the scientific advances in the field of bone density assessment and interpretation.  Presentations on fracture risk assessment based on bone density results will be a major focus of the meeting.  The program will include presentations of new scientific data, as well as reviews of the literature and published studies over the preceding year.  Accepted abstracts and posters representing new work in the field of bone densitometry, osteoporosis and treatments will be available for poster viewing.  State of the art equipment and applications will also be presented.  Attendees can expect to further their knowledge of bone density technology, interpretation and application to clinical practice.  02/16/2005  2005  02

title: Spine Care: Treatment Innovations for Your Patients
search_all: Spine Care: Treatment Innovations for Your Patients Course  Live Eight out of ten adults will experience an acute episode of back pain at some point in their lifetime.  While most episodes of back pain are self-limited, 5% to 10% of cases will become chronic. title: Preventing & Treating Thromboembolic Disease: Defining the State-of-the-Art
search_all: Preventing & Treating Thromboembolic Disease: Defining the State-of-the-Art Course  Live Venous thromboembolish (VTE) is the third most common thrombosis-related disorder and a major cause of morbidity and mortality in hospitalized patients.  Autopsy studies reveal that the majority of patients who suffer a fatal pulmonary embolism (PD) have not undergone recent surgery, (1) but PE is rarely suspected as a cause of death in nonsurgical patients. (2) As many as 1 in 20 hospitalized medical patients with multiple problems and severe immobility may suffer a fatal pulmonary embolism but thromboprophylaxis is infrequently used in medical patients, despite 20 consensus statements urging its more widespread use.  04/15/2005  2005  04

title: Migraine Headache Throughout The Lifespan
search_all: Migraine Headache Throughout The Lifespan Course  Live Migraine headache afflicts 28 million Americans and represents one of the most common diseases encountered by health care providers.  The disease spans the human lifespan often beginning during childhood and continuing throughout the adult years.  Migraine headache can be influenced by age, hormonal events and coexisting medical diseases.  Conversely the presence of migraine headach can complicate the management of other medial disorders (e.g. cardiac, renal, or liver disease, malignancy, transplant, HIV).  This unique seminar will discuss the management of migraine headache in children, women and the elderly.  Participants will also learn how medical diseases affect the presentation and treatment of migraine headache.  Dr. David, our keynote speaker and an internationally renowned headache expert, will present the clinical data to support the practice of "early abortive treatment" of migraine headache.  He will also discuss the cardiovascular safety of the triptans.  04/30/2005  2005  04

title: Burned Patients: Anesthesia Considerations
search_all:
Burned Patients: Anesthesia Considerations Internet Activity Enduring Material Internet Enduring Enduring Material

Objectives

  • Describe burn classification by type and degree of burn.
  • Identify the physiologic changes that occur in response to all types of burns and to describe the medical/surgical treatment of complications resulting from these changes.
  • Formulate an anesthetic strategy to manage burned patients; preoperative assessment; patient transport; intraoperative fluid, blood, ventilation and temperature concerns; and postoperative considerations.
  • Identify drugs useful in the anesthetic management of burned patients based on alterations in volumes of distribution, protein binding, hepatic and renal clearance and drug tolerance.
